:QUOTE
The cartridge razor taught a generation the wrong fundamentals. A safety razor unlearns them in one shave.

:INFO
Why Technique Changes Everything
A double-edge safety razor uses a single sharp blade instead of multiple dull \
blades stacked to simulate a close shave. It requires three things a cartridge \
razor does not: a correct angle, zero applied pressure, and knowledge of your \
personal hair growth direction. Done right, a safety razor delivers less \
irritation, fewer ingrown hairs, and a closer result than any cartridge system.

:COUNTER.half
30 Degrees
Blade angle to skin
|
:COUNTER.half
Zero Pressure
Weight of the razor only — never push

:PATH
Map Your Grain Before the First Shave
Let stubble grow 2 to 3 days. Run a finger across your cheek, jaw, and neck \
in different directions. The direction that feels rough is against the grain. \
The direction that feels smooth is with the grain. Draw a simple map on paper. \
Grain often runs in three or four different directions across the face and neck. \
Shaving against the grain without preparation causes razor burn and ingrown hairs.

:PATH
Prepare Your Face and Lather
Start with a warm shower or press a hot damp towel against your face for 60 to \
90 seconds. Heat softens the hair shaft and opens pores. Wet your face before \
applying lather. Load a shaving brush by swirling on a puck of shaving soap for \
30 seconds, then build lather on your face in circular motions for another 30 \
seconds. Lather should be dense and glossy, not foamy or thin.

:INFO
Reading Good Lather
Thin, foamy lather provides no glide and allows blade drag across the skin. \
Dense, glossy lather acts as a protective cushion. If your lather looks like \
aerosol shaving foam, add less water to the brush. If lather balls up and dries \
immediately, add more water. The ideal texture resembles thick Greek yogurt — \
it holds soft peaks and does not drip from the face.

:PATH
The Three-Pass Technique
Pass 1 — WTG (with the grain): short strokes following the direction hair grows. \
This removes the bulk of stubble without irritation. Rinse and re-lather. Pass 2 \
— XTG (across the grain): stroke perpendicular to hair growth direction. This \
refines the shave significantly. Rinse and re-lather. Pass 3 — ATG (against the \
grain): stroke against the growth direction. Only attempt this pass after you \
have mastered the first two passes over several sessions.

:COUNTER.half
2 to 3 cm Per Stroke
Short strokes, rinse razor frequently
|
:COUNTER.half
30 to 35 Degree Angle
Place cap flat on skin, lower handle until blade engages

:PATH
Finish and Treat the Skin
Rinse with cold water to close pores. Rub a wet alum block across the shaved \
area — it stings at any nicks and tightens skin through its astringent \
properties. Rinse the alum off after 30 seconds. Apply an unscented aftershave \
balm if your skin runs dry, or an alcohol-based aftershave splash for toning \
and scent. Moisturizer extends the window before your next shave.

:CHECKLIST
First Shave Preparation
[ ] Grain map completed on 2 to 3 days of stubble growth
[ ] Razor loaded with a fresh blade
[ ] Shaving brush soaked in hot water for 1 minute before building lather
[ ] Hot towel or post-shower prep completed before lathering
[ ] Alum block and aftershave ready for the finish

:NOTE
Razor Burn vs Blade Irritation
Razor burn is red, hot, blotchy skin caused by too much pressure or shaving \
against the grain without adequate preparation. It fades within hours. Blade \
irritation appears as small red bumps along the shave path and is caused by a \
dull blade pulling hair rather than cutting it. Change blades every 3 to 5 shaves. \
A blade that felt sharp yesterday can drag today. Trust the sensation, not a \
fixed schedule.

:QUOTE
A safety razor teaches your hand not to push. That lesson transfers to everything that requires a light touch.

